ons\": [\n        \"Add explicit glyoxylate synthesis or import from another connected route.\",\n        \"Acknowledge kinetic competition with pyruvate and oxaloacetate as highlighted by Mayer and Moran 2022 and Kaur et al. 2024.\",\n        \"Include temperature constraints that avoid excessive glutamate degradation/cyclization.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.7,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.83\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.8,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.86,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.89,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n      \"feedback\": \"The photocatalytic pyrite-surface amination step is plausible and matches the reviewed literature trend, but it is less established than the transamination and NADH routes. The pathway is coherent and cross-environmental, yet somewhat speculative in exact substrate scope and selectivity for alpha-ketoglutarate relative to other alpha-keto acids.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_009\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Specify UV conditions and pyrite-surface context more explicitly.\",\n        \"Clarify whether the cited pyrite photocatalysis directly demonstrated glutamate from alpha-ketoglutarate or is being generalized.\",\n        \"Add glyoxylate formation to avoid a gap in the carbon network.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.95\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.95,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.96,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.92,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is the cleanest two-step route in the network and arguably the best literature match for direct glutamate production from plausible intermediates. Metal-free glyoxylate + pyruvate to alpha-ketoglutarate is strongly supported by Stubbs et al. 2020, and the glycine transamination endpoint is among the highest-yield glutamate-forming prebiotic reactions reported. Its only weakness is that it begins from relatively advanced intermediates and does not itself show the full Hydrothermal to Surface to Biochemical progression.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Embed this route into a fuller upstream network by explicitly connecting glyoxylate and pyruvate formation.\",\n        \"Keep the stepwise framing because this route is individually strong even if full one-pot integration remains unresolved.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.91,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.89\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.88,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.9,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.84,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.9,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.88,\n      \"feedback\": \"The acrolein-based Strecker route is a strong classical pathway and aligns well with Van Trump and Miller 1972 and Parker et al. 2011. The aminonitrile-to-glutamate hydrolysis logic is sound. Main issue is that acrolein is introduced without synthesis in the network, and the aminonitrile molecular formula appears questionable for a glutamate aminonitrile intermediate.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Correct and verify the structure/formula of the glutamate aminonitrile node.\",\n        \"Add a plausible prebiotic source for acrolein or explicitly note it as an imported atmospheric product.\",\n        \"Clarify whether Michael addition precedes Strecker capture in the mechanistic description.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.89,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.87,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.9,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.9,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.88,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway is well grounded in the Bucherer-Bergs literature and is one of the more convincing alternative routes from alpha-ketoglutarate. It is coherent and chemically sound. As with other alpha-ketoglutarate-based routes, the missing explicit production of glyoxylate weakens the full network linkage.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Add explicit source chemistry for glyoxylate and alpha-ketoglutarate precursors.\",\n        \"State whether CO2 or carbonate is involved if following classic Bucherer-Bergs conditions more closely.\",\n        \"Clarify hydrolysis conditions for the hydantoin to glutamate conversion.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.8,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.79,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.81,\n      \"feedback\": \"This route is literature-supported in a product-mixture sense: HCN oligomerization followed by hydrolysis can release glutamate among many products. It is weaker than the alpha-ketoglutarate routes because selectivity is low and the 'mixture' node obscures mechanistic detail. Still, it is appropriate as a minor convergent route and matches Ferris et al. 1978.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_015\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Explicitly note the concentration requirement for HCN polymerization and likely need for eutectic concentration